"""
MKT Context Commentary — Exodus 22–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-exodus-22-24.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/exodus.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/exodus.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/exodus.json (existing entries)

Key decisions in this range:
- Code of Hammurabi parallels noted for property law (ch22) without claiming literary dependence
- "Widow/orphan/stranger" triad identified as the primary protected-class formula in ANE ethics
- Three annual festivals (ch23:14-17) identified with their ANE agricultural roots
- The angel (23:20) discussed as the divine mediating figure whose identity is debated
- Covenant ratification ceremony (ch24) analyzed as suzerainty-treaty protocol
- The elders' vision of God (24:9-11) treated as a remarkable throne-room theophany
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CONTEXT = {
    "22": {
        "1": "<p>Exodus 22 continues the Book of the Covenant (Exod 20:22–23:33), Israel's earliest law code. The ox/sheep theft law opens with a principle found also in the Code of Hammurabi (§8): theft of cattle is punished by a multiplied penalty. The fivefold restitution for an ox and fourfold for a sheep reflect the animal's economic value — oxen were draft animals whose loss disrupted the entire agricultural year, making their theft more damaging. These are case laws (<em>mišpāṭîm</em>), framed as conditional statements ('If anyone does X, then Y'), structurally identical to other ANE legal collections.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The night-burglar law is among the most nuanced in the ancient world: killing a thief in the act at night is not murder (no blood-guilt), but killing him during daylight is. The distinction tracks on visibility — at night, there is no way to know if the intruder is a burglar or an assassin; the threat is genuinely life-threatening. By day, the homeowner can see the situation and respond proportionally. Roman law makes a parallel distinction (Twelve Tables 8.12-13). The law demonstrates that even property crimes do not automatically justify lethal force.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The 'sold to pay for his theft' clause — if a thief has nothing, he is sold into debt-slavery to make restitution — shows the Book of the Covenant's economic realism. ANE legal collections consistently address the problem of the insolvent debtor; debt-slavery was the standard mechanism for resolving unpayable debt. Leviticus 25 later sets temporal limits (six years maximum, Jubilee release) on such servitude, distinguishing Israelite debt-slavery from chattel slavery. The system presupposes that human dignity survives debt: the thief is sold to work, not permanently owned.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The double-restitution principle for found stolen property provides a lesser penalty than the fivefold/fourfold rule of v.1, because the animal is still alive — the full economic harm has not occurred. Ancient Near Eastern law collections similarly grade penalties by outcome: the Code of Lipit-Ishtar (§d) and the Laws of Eshnunna (§§12-13) scale theft penalties according to the nature of the property and its recovery. The proportionality principle — penalty calibrated to actual damage — runs throughout the Book of the Covenant.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The liability law for grazing damage reflects the agricultural realities of ancient Canaan: fields and vineyards were enclosed by walls or hedges, and livestock straying into a neighbor's crops was a recurring dispute. The principle is clear: the owner of the animal bears responsibility for any damage it causes. Similar liability principles appear in the Laws of Eshnunna (§§53-58) governing water damage and crop damage from breached dikes. The Book of the Covenant is not borrowing from these codes but addresses the same practical realities of agricultural community life.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The fire liability law addresses a common hazard in grain-harvest season: fire set to clear stubble or thornbushes that spreads to a neighbor's uncut grain. The dry Palestinian summer (May-October) made such fires genuinely dangerous. The principle of negligence liability — if you started the fire, you pay for damage you could not fully control — reflects a sophisticated understanding of causation in law. The grain harvest setting ties this to the period just before the Feast of Harvest (23:16), when such fires would have been most common.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The safekeeping law (vv.7-15) addresses a distinct social practice: entrusting property to a neighbor for temporary custody. In a society without banking institutions, trusted neighbors served as informal depositories. The neighbor who accepts custody assumes a fiduciary responsibility — not absolute liability (if a thief breaks in, the trustee is not responsible), but responsibility to not steal or misappropriate. The appeal 'before God' (<em>hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) for disputed cases likely refers to an oath-taking ceremony at the sanctuary, where YHWH is invoked as the ultimate judge of what cannot be externally verified.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'Must appear before God' (<em>yiqrab ʾel hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — the Hebrew word translated as 'God' here may refer to divine representatives (judges), as reflected in the LXX's <em>ἐνώπιον τοῦ κριτηρίου τοῦ θεοῦ</em> (before the divine tribunal). The ambiguity reflects the practice of oath-taking before YHWH in difficult cases — the sanctuary or local shrine was the court of appeal when human testimony conflicted. The deterrent effect of a divine oath was significant in a society where supernatural accountability was taken seriously: swearing falsely before YHWH risked divine punishment.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The general principle for disputed ownership (v.9) extends the adjudication-before-God principle to any contested property — animal, garment, or unspecified lost item claimed by two parties. 'Whom God declares guilty (<em>yĕrašîʿūn ʾĕlōhîm</em>) shall pay double to the other' establishes the proportional penalty for false ownership claims. The doubling penalty for dishonest claims parallels the Code of Hammurabi §120 (where the person who falsely claims another's goods must pay double). The shared penalty structure reflects the universal logic of deterrence: make fraudulent claims costly.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The bailment law for animals (vv.10-13) covers a different category: not storing property but loaning a working animal. Loaned animals are exposed to working risks that a stored item is not — injury, predation, theft. The law distinguishes: YHWH-sworn oath covers death/injury/disappearance with no evidence (v.10-11), but theft carries liability because the bailee should have protected it (v.12), and predation carries no liability if evidence is produced (v.13). This graduated liability system is more sophisticated than the Code of Hammurabi's treatment of herding contracts (§§264-267).</p>",
        "11": "<p>The oath before YHWH for contested animal deaths introduces the concept of YHWH as the guarantor of oaths in cases where human verification is impossible. In ANE legal practice, divine oaths were a last resort for cases with no witness — the deity was invoked as the omniscient witness who would punish perjury. Numbers 5:11-31 (the suspected adultery trial) is the most elaborate biblical example of this principle. The theological assumption is that YHWH knows what happened even when humans cannot determine it, making a false oath an act of defiance against divine omniscience.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The distinction between an animal stolen from a bailee (bailee liable) and one killed by a predator (bailee not liable) tracks on preventability: theft should have been prevented by proper care, but predation is an unforeseeable force of nature. The same principle underlies modern insurance law's concept of 'act of God' — certain risks are uninsurable because they lie outside human control. The Book of the Covenant's sophistication here reflects centuries of practical community dispute-resolution before being codified.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'If it was torn by a wild animal, let him bring it as evidence (<em>yĕbîʾēhā ʿēd</em>)' — the principle of producing physical evidence to support an exemption claim is consistent with ANE legal practice. The Laws of Eshnunna (§37) similarly require evidence when a stolen animal is claimed to have died. The evidence (the torn remains) makes the claim verifiable rather than relying solely on oath. The combination of physical evidence and oath is the ancient world's two-witness principle — both material and testimonial evidence were required for the most weighty legal exemptions.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The animal-borrowing law (vv.14-15) distinguishes borrowed from hired animals: a borrowed animal is borrowed gratis and its owner is elsewhere, making the borrower fully responsible for any mishap. A hired animal is different — the owner's fee already factors in risk, transferring some liability back to the owner. This reflects economic reasoning: when the owner charges for use, the risk premium is built into the price. The same distinction between gratuitous and compensated bailment runs through Roman law and modern contract law, suggesting this is a universal commercial logic rather than a uniquely Israelite innovation.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The seduction of an unbetrothed virgin (vv.16-17) is treated as a property violation — the bride-price (<em>mohar</em>) is the economic remedy, regardless of whether marriage follows. The bride-price was not a purchase but a gift to the bride's family that established the groom's seriousness and compensated the family for the loss of their daughter. The father's right to refuse the marriage (v.17) while still receiving the bride-price acknowledges both his authority over his household and the community's interest in deterring casual sexual exploitation. Deuteronomy 22:28-29 adds that the man must marry the woman and cannot divorce her.</p>",
        "16": "<p>See note on v.15 — the bride-price law addresses the economic dimension of sexual exploitation. The Code of Hammurabi (§155-156) addresses similar cases with death penalties for some categories; the Book of the Covenant's remedy is economic compensation rather than death, except where the act is aggravated by betrothal (Deut 22:23-27, where it is treated as assault and potentially capital). The differentiation reflects a nuanced understanding of the range of violation: the unbetrothed case is primarily a property wrong; the betrothed case is analogous to murder because a prior covenant exists.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'Do not allow a sorceress (<em>mĕkaššēpāh</em>) to live' — the prohibition on sorcery appears throughout the ANE: Hammurabi's law code opens with a sorcery case (§2). In Israel's context, divination and magic were associated with Canaanite religion and represented direct competition with YHWH's sovereignty over the future. The term <em>kāšap</em> covers various forms of occult practice. The female form (<em>mĕkaššēpāh</em>) may reflect the reality that women were more commonly associated with such practices in ancient Israelite society, but Deut 18:10-11 uses inclusive language. Saul's consultation of the medium at Endor (1 Sam 28) illustrates both the prohibition and the sociological reality that such practitioners persisted.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Bestiality (<em>šōkēb ʿim bĕhēmāh</em>) is a capital crime in the Book of the Covenant (v.19), Leviticus 18:23 and 20:15-16, and Deuteronomy 27:21. The absolute prohibition distinguishes the Israelite law code from surrounding cultures where mythological accounts of divine-animal unions were part of the cosmological narrative (Egyptian, Canaanite, Greek traditions). The prohibition enforces a categorical boundary between human and animal that is grounded in the creation narrative: humans are made in the divine image (<em>tselem ʾĕlōhîm</em>, Gen 1:26-27), giving human sexuality a covenantal dignity that excludes animal partners.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The death penalty for sacrifice to other gods (v.20) is the covenant's most fundamental protection: the Sinai covenant is an exclusive relationship, and any worship directed to another deity is a breach of the fundamental obligation. The verb <em>yāḥāram</em> (devoted/destroyed) is the same root as <em>ḥērem</em> — the total dedication to YHWH through destruction applied to the Canaanite cities in Joshua. The theological principle is that divided loyalty in covenant is not a lesser violation but a category error — like bigamy in a monogamous marriage, it voids the entire relationship.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'Do not mistreat or oppress a foreigner (<em>gēr</em>), for you were foreigners in Egypt' — this is the first statement of the ethical principle that grounds Israelite treatment of the vulnerable in Israel's own formative experience of vulnerability. The <em>gēr</em> (resident alien/foreigner) was a legally vulnerable class — lacking the family networks, property rights, and civic standing that native Israelites possessed. The exodus argument ('you were foreigners in Egypt') is repeated over thirty times in the OT as the motivational basis for social ethics. It is the earliest example in world literature of historical empathy as an ethical foundation.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The widow-and-orphan protection clause (vv.22-24) places these two groups alongside the <em>gēr</em> as the primary triad of the vulnerable. The widow-orphan-stranger triad appears throughout the OT prophets (Isa 1:17; Jer 7:6; Zech 7:10; Mal 3:5) and is the defining measure of social justice in Israelite ethics. The Code of Hammurabi's prologue also mentions widows and orphans as those the king protects, but the Israelite version is more radical: YHWH himself is their defender, and mistreating them brings his direct judgment (vv.23-24).</p>",
        "22": "<p>The specific verb used here — <em>ʿinnîtem</em> (afflict, oppress, humble) — is the same verb used for Egypt's oppression of Israel in Exod 1:11-12. The ethical logic is closing the circle: YHWH freed Israel from being oppressed; therefore Israel must not oppress. The widow and orphan are not merely pitiable objects of charity but persons whose mistreatment is directly analogous to Pharaoh's mistreatment of Israel. James 1:27 identifies care for orphans and widows as the defining mark of pure religion, standing directly in this tradition.</p>",
        "23": "<p>'If you do and they cry out to me (<em>wayyiṣʿăqû ʾēlay</em>)' — the same verb <em>ṣāʿaq</em> is used for Israel's crying out under Egyptian oppression (Exod 2:23; 3:7). YHWH's promise to hear the cry of the widow and orphan uses the same language as his hearing Israel's cry in Egypt, making the structural parallel explicit: just as YHWH responded to Israel's cry, he will respond to the cry of those Israel oppresses. This is one of the OT's most direct statements of YHWH's identification with the poor.</p>",
        "24": "<p>YHWH's anger aroused to the point of killing with the sword and making the offender's family into the very vulnerable persons he failed to protect (your wives become widows, your children orphans) — this is the lex talionis principle applied at the social level: the oppressor becomes the oppressed. The threat transforms the abstract command into a visceral self-interest argument: if you oppress the vulnerable, you risk making your own family vulnerable. The social ethics here are not merely humanitarian but covenantal consequences enforced by YHWH himself.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The prohibition on charging interest (<em>nešek</em>, literally 'bite') to fellow Israelites — specifically the poor — reflects the covenant community's understanding of itself as a family (<em>ʿammî</em>, 'my people') where exploiting the desperate is a betrayal of kinship. Ancient Near Eastern loan contracts routinely charged 20-33% interest on grain loans and silver loans; the Book of the Covenant prohibits this within the covenant community. The distinction between lending within the community and commercial transactions with outsiders reflects the covenantal boundary: economic solidarity applies first within Israel (Deut 23:19-20 explicitly permits interest from foreigners).</p>",
        "26": "<p>The cloak-pledge law addresses a specific form of poverty exploitation: taking a person's outer garment (<em>śalmāh</em>) as collateral for a loan. In the ancient Near East, the outer cloak was a multipurpose garment used both as daily clothing and as a sleeping blanket in the cold Palestinian nights. To hold it overnight was to expose the borrower to genuine physical hardship. The law's return-by-sunset provision is not merely humanitarian but theological: the cloak is not the lender's property to hold at will; it belongs to the covenant community's member whose dignity must be maintained even in debt.</p>",
        "27": "<p>'That cloak is the only covering he has for his body. What else will he sleep in? When he cries out to me, I will hear, for I am compassionate (<em>ḥannûn ʾănî</em>).' The divine self-characterization as <em>ḥannûn</em> (gracious, compassionate) is the same word used in the thirteen attributes of mercy (Exod 34:6). The connection is deliberate: YHWH's own character is the foundation for the social ethics he requires. God who is compassionate to the poor requires his people to embody the same compassion — this is the 'imitation of God' ethic (<em>imitatio Dei</em>) that becomes explicit in Leviticus 19:2 ('Be holy for I, YHWH your God, am holy').</p>",
        "28": "<p>'Do not blaspheme God (<em>ʾĕlōhîm</em>) or curse the ruler (<em>nāśî</em>) of your people' — the term <em>nāśî</em> (chieftain, prince, one who is lifted up) is used for tribal leaders rather than the later royal term <em>melek</em> (king). This suggests the law's formulation in a pre-monarchic context. Acts 23:5 quotes this verse when Paul apologizes for speaking against the high priest, showing the law's continued authority in Second Temple Judaism. The coupling of divine and civil authority under the same prohibition reflects the covenant's structure: YHWH is king; the <em>nāśî</em> exercises delegated authority; both command respect.</p>",
        "29": "<p>The firstfruits and firstborn dedication (vv.29-30) returns to the theme of Ch.13: everything that 'first opens the womb' or 'first ripens' belongs to YHWH. The agricultural firstfruits (rîʾšîtĕkā — the first of your yield) were presented at the sanctuary as an acknowledgment that the land and its produce are YHWH's gift. 'The firstborn of your sons you shall give to me' — the redemption mechanism (see Exod 13:12-15; Num 18:15-16) means the sons are redeemed by a payment, not literally sacrificed. The law counters the Canaanite practice of child sacrifice by establishing a different mechanism for the firstborn's dedication.</p>",
        "30": "<p>'Seven days the firstborn shall remain with its mother; on the eighth day you shall give it to me' — the seven-day waiting period before presenting the firstborn animal echoes the circumcision law (Gen 17:12; Lev 12:3): the eighth day is the threshold of formal covenant entry. The same structure applies: natural birth (days 1-7) is completed by a covenantal act on the eighth day. This pattern — seven days of natural process followed by an eighth-day covenant marker — is embedded in Israelite ritual: the dedication of the tabernacle (Exod 29:35-37), the cleansing of a leper (Lev 14:8-10), and the ordination of priests (Lev 8-9) all follow it.</p>",
        "31": "<p>'You are to be my holy people (<em>ʿam qādôš</em>)' — this is the covenant community's defining identity statement, appearing here in the context of food law (not eating torn meat). The holiness is not primarily about ritual purity but about covenantal distinctiveness: Israel is set apart to YHWH, and that set-apartness manifests in every domain of life, including diet. The prohibition on eating <em>tĕrēpāh</em> (torn prey) — meat from an animal killed by another animal — is a negative boundary marker: the holy people do not eat what the beasts of the field eat. This holiness-through-boundary-maintenance runs through Leviticus 11-15 and is the foundation of the purity laws.</p>"
    },
    "23": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 23 opens with a cluster of judicial-ethics commands that address the most tempting forms of procedural injustice: false testimony, mob justice, and class-based partiality. The prohibition on 'spreading false reports' (<em>šēmaʿ šāwĕ'</em>, empty/false report) addresses the pre-trial stage of reputation damage — gossip and slander that prejudice the community before a case reaches formal adjudication. The prohibition on being 'a malicious witness' (<em>ʿēd ḥāmās</em>, violent/destroying witness) addresses testimony in court. Both target the same reality: legal systems are only as honest as the people who use them.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'Do not follow the crowd (<em>rabbîm</em>, the many) in doing wrong' — this is a striking counter-cultural command in a society where communal conformity was the default. The specific application is judicial: majority opinion does not determine truth or justice. The Talmudic principle that a unanimous verdict in a capital case is suspicious (Sanhedrin 17a — if everyone votes guilty, perhaps the accused had no real advocate) may derive from this principle. The law protects the minority opinion in legal proceedings — a single honest voice against a corrupt majority is more valuable than unanimity in injustice.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'Do not show favoritism to a poor person in a lawsuit (<em>riblô dāl bĕrîbô</em>)' — this stands in apparent tension with the general protection of the poor. The law distinguishes between social mercy (the poor should receive help) and legal impartiality (the poor are not automatically right in disputes). Leviticus 19:15 makes this explicit: 'You shall not be partial to the poor or defer to the great, but in righteousness shall you judge your neighbor.' Justice is blind in both directions: favoring the poor in court because they are poor is as unjust as favoring the wealthy because they are powerful.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'If you come across your enemy's ox or donkey wandering off, be sure to return it' — the enemy-help commands (vv.4-5) extend the love-of-neighbor principle to the enemy, making them among the most demanding commands in the Book of the Covenant. The Law of Moses does not require loving enemies as equals (that is Jesus's extension in Matt 5:43-48), but it does require practical assistance even when personal hostility exists. The property at stake (a wandering animal) represents a significant economic loss; returning it is a costly act of justice that overrides personal animosity. Jesus cites this principle's trajectory in Matt 5:44.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'If you see the donkey of someone who hates you (<em>śōnĕʾăkā</em>) fallen down under its load, do not leave it there; be sure to help them' — the fallen-donkey command requires active intervention to prevent an enemy's animal from suffering. The phrasing 'you shall refrain from leaving him' (<em>ʿāzōb taʿăzōb ʿimmô</em>) is intensive — not merely permission but requirement. Donkeys loaded beyond capacity was a common cruelty of ancient transport; the law protects both the animal from continued suffering and the owner from economic loss. Animal welfare is embedded in Israel's law code centuries before it becomes an explicit philosophical concern.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'Do not deny justice to your poor people in their lawsuits (<em>bĕrîbô</em>)' — this commands impartiality in favor of the poor's due process rights, balanced by v.3's command not to favor them. The poor are not automatically right, but they are entitled to equal access to justice. In ancient courts, the wealthy could afford advocates, bribes, and influence; the poor had neither resources nor social capital. The Book of the Covenant does not legislate a system for addressing this inequality but commands the individual judge and witness to resist it — a demand for personal integrity in the face of systemic pressure.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'Have nothing to do with a false charge (<em>dĕbar šeqer</em>) and do not put an innocent or honest person to death' — the prohibition on false charges directly addresses capital cases, where the stakes are highest. 'For I will not acquit the guilty (<em>lōʾ-ʾaṣaddîq rāšāʿ</em>)' — YHWH's own judicial standard is absolute: he does not acquit the actually guilty regardless of who advocates for them. This is the background for the prophetic complaint against corrupt courts (Amos 5:10-12; Micah 3:11) and for Isaiah's portrait of the ultimate just judge (Isa 11:3-5) who will judge with perfect equity.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'Do not accept a bribe (<em>šōḥad</em>), for a bribe blinds those who see and twists the words of the innocent' — the 'blinds those who see' clause is a remarkable psychological observation: bribery does not merely corrupt the decision but corrupts the perception. Judges who accept bribes begin genuinely to see the case differently; the bribe shapes their reasoning rather than merely overriding it. This insight — that financial interest distorts cognition, not just decisions — is more sophisticated than a simple prohibition on corruption. Deuteronomy 16:19 repeats this with the added phrase 'even the righteous,' implying that even good-faith judges can be unconsciously corrupted by money.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Do not oppress a foreigner; you yourselves know how it feels to be foreigners, because you were foreigners in Egypt' — the second occurrence of the 'you were foreigners in Egypt' ethic (see 22:21). The empathy argument ('you know how it feels') makes the prohibition not merely a legal command but a moral appeal to experiential understanding. The verb <em>yĕdaʿtem ʾet nepeš haggēr</em> (you know the soul/experience of the stranger) is the same verb used for Adam 'knowing' Eve in Gen 4:1 — intimate, lived knowledge, not abstract information. This is perhaps the deepest grounding of social ethics in the OT: historical suffering as the source of moral understanding.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The sabbatical-year law for land (vv.10-11) extends the Sabbath principle from time (the weekly day of rest) to space (the arable land) and to economic relationships (the poor and the animals). The seventh year of lying fallow (<em>šĕmiṭṭāh</em>, release) served multiple purposes: ecological (soil regeneration), social (the poor could glean freely), and theological (acknowledgment that the land belongs to YHWH and is only loaned to Israel). Leviticus 25 elaborates this into a full Sabbath Year system with debt remission. The NT letter's theme of Jubilee release (Luke 4:18-19) draws directly on this trajectory.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'During the seventh year let the land lie unplowed and unused. Then the poor among your people may get food from it, and the wild animals may eat what is left' — the sabbatical yield is not owned by the farmer but is commons: first the poor, then wildlife. This is the earliest 'food security' legislation in the ancient world. The social logic is that the natural productivity of the land in its rest year belongs first to those who cannot otherwise eat. The law assumes that if the farmer cannot harvest, the poor will not starve — YHWH will ensure the land's seventh-year yield is sufficient for everyone who eats from it.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The Sabbath day of rest (v.12) is here given a humanitarian rationale — so that the ox, donkey, slave, and foreigner may rest. This expands the Decalogue's Sabbath command (Exod 20:8-10) which already lists similar beneficiaries, emphasizing that Sabbath is not merely a religious duty but an embedded social institution for protecting the laboring class. The slave and the foreigner are explicitly named: both are outside the covenant core but included in its protections. Deuteronomy 5:15 adds the exodus motivation ('remember you were slaves'), tying the Sabbath rest to the liberation narrative.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'Be careful to do everything I have said to you. Do not invoke the names of other gods (<em>lōʾ tazkîrû</em>); do not let them be heard on your lips' — the covenant exclusivity command that frames the entire Book of the Covenant. The specific prohibition on speaking the names of other gods in worship or oath goes beyond the Decalogue's prohibition on having other gods, reaching to the habit of casual invocation. In ANE culture, speaking a deity's name in an oath or blessing was an act of cultic allegiance; this law prohibits that practice even informally. YHWH's jealousy (Exod 20:5; 34:14) extends to linguistic allegiance, not just formal worship.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Three annual pilgrim festivals (vv.14-17) are here commanded — the earliest festival calendar in the Torah. The three correspond to the three agricultural seasons: spring barley harvest (Unleavened Bread/Passover), early summer wheat harvest (Feast of Harvest/Weeks/Shavuot), and fall fruit harvest (Feast of Ingathering/Tabernacles/Sukkot). All adult Israelite males were to 'appear before the Lord' (<em>yērāʾeh ʾel-pĕnê hāʾādōn YHWH</em>) at the central sanctuary three times a year. The agricultural framing grounds Israel's covenant calendar in the land's natural cycles — YHWH is not only the God of the exodus but the God of harvest.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The Festival of Unleavened Bread (<em>ḥag hammaṣṣôt</em>) in the month of Abib (Nisan/March-April) is tied directly to the exodus: 'as I commanded you, at the appointed time in the month of Abib, for in it you came out of Egypt.' The agricultural festival (barley harvest begins) and the historical commemoration (the exodus) have been permanently fused. 'No one shall appear before me empty-handed (<em>rêqām</em>)' — the presentation of an offering was the essential act of pilgrimage, acknowledging that the worshiper comes as a supplicant before a divine host, not merely as a tourist.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The Feast of Harvest (<em>ḥag haqqāṣîr</em>), later called Shavuot (Weeks) or Pentecost (fifty days after Passover), celebrates the firstfruits of the wheat harvest in May-June. The Feast of Ingathering (<em>ḥag hāʾāsîp</em>), later called Sukkot (Tabernacles), falls at the end of the agricultural year (September-October) when grapes, figs, olives, and other fall fruits have been gathered. In Second Temple Judaism, Shavuot was reinterpreted as the anniversary of the giving of the Torah at Sinai; Pentecost in Acts 2 occurs on that same festival, making the giving of the Spirit a new-covenant parallel to the giving of the Law.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'Three times a year all your men are to appear before the Lord, the LORD (<em>ʾel-pĕnê hāʾādōn YHWH</em>)' — the double title 'the Lord, YHWH' (<em>ʾādôn YHWH</em>) emphasizes both the universal lordship and the covenant-name. The pilgrimage requirement was practically significant: it required leaving home and farm three times annually, demonstrating that covenant loyalty overrides economic calculation. The Second Temple system of pilgrimage to Jerusalem became the center of Jewish communal life; Josephus describes enormous crowds for the three festivals. Jesus's final Passover pilgrimage (Luke 9:51; John 12:12) was one of these annual ascents.</p>",
        "18": "<p>'Do not offer the blood of a sacrifice with anything containing yeast (<em>ḥāmēṣ</em>)' — leaven was excluded from all blood sacrifices (Lev 2:11) because of its association with fermentation/corruption. The fat of the festival offering must not remain until morning — it must be entirely consumed. These two regulations frame the offering as belonging completely to YHWH: no contamination from leaven, no remnant for human storage. The prohibition on mixing leaven with blood sacrifices is the liturgical counterpart to the Passover's removal of all leaven — the threshold between the old (leavened Egypt) and the new (unleavened covenant life) must be absolutely maintained.</p>",
        "19": "<p>'Bring the best of the firstfruits of your soil to the house of the LORD your God' — the firstfruits (<em>rēʾšît bikkûrê ʾadmātĕkā</em>) are the ritual acknowledgment that the land's produce belongs first to YHWH. 'You shall not boil a young goat in its mother's milk' — this enigmatic prohibition has generated two main interpretations: (1) it is a rejection of a specific Canaanite fertility rite (though evidence for such a rite is contested), or (2) it reflects a natural-law principle against the grotesque inversion of a mother's nurturing milk being used to kill her offspring. All three references to this prohibition (Exod 23:19; 34:26; Deut 14:21) became the foundation of the elaborate kosher laws separating meat and dairy products.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'I am sending an angel (<em>malʾāk</em>) ahead of you to guard you along the way' — the identity of this angel has been debated from ancient times. The commands that follow (v.21: 'My name is in him') suggest this is more than an ordinary messenger; YHWH's name dwelling in the angel implies YHWH's personal presence in this figure. Jewish interpretation (Philo, Maimonides) identified this angel as the Logos or divine reason; patristic writers identified him as the pre-incarnate Son. The angel who will lead Israel to the promised land is the same figure who appeared at the burning bush (Exod 3:2) and who goes before Israel as the pillar of cloud and fire.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'Pay attention to him and listen to what he says. Do not rebel against him; he will not forgive your rebellion, since my name is in him' — the phrase 'my name is in him' (<em>šĕmî bĕqirbô</em>) is the most emphatic possible statement of divine presence: the name of YHWH — which is his identity, character, and presence — inhabits this angelic figure. To rebel against him is to rebel against YHWH himself, with no forgiving intermediary. The NT applies this logic to Jesus: 'He who rejects me rejects him who sent me' (Luke 10:16), and John's Gospel identifies Jesus as the one in whom the Father's name dwells (John 17:11-12).</p>",
        "22": "<p>The conditional covenant formula: 'If you listen carefully to what he says and do all that I say, I will be an enemy to your enemies.' YHWH's military assistance is tied to covenant obedience — not as a transaction but as the natural outworking of covenant loyalty. YHWH fights for those who are his; those who break covenant step outside his protection. The promise here forms the theological framework for the entire conquest narrative in Joshua: Israel's military success will be precisely proportional to covenant fidelity, and military failure (Achan's sin in Josh 7) will be traced directly to covenant violation.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Six nations are listed as the inhabitants of Canaan whom the angel will drive out. This list (Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Canaanites, Hivites, Jebusites) is one of several in the Torah with slightly varying membership; the Perizzites (possibly 'village-dwellers,' a non-ethnic designation) and the distinctive naming of the Jebusites (controlling Jerusalem) reflect actual population memory from the pre-settlement period. The archaeological record confirms the Late Bronze Age diversity of Canaanite city-states — each with its own political structure and cult, making the 'nations' list descriptively accurate at the population level.</p>",
        "24": "<p>'You must demolish them and break their sacred stones (<em>maṣṣēbôt</em>) to pieces' — the sacred standing stones were ubiquitous in Canaanite cult sites, serving as focal points for worship and oath-taking. Archaeological excavations at Canaanite sites (Hazor, Gezer, Megiddo) have found arrays of standing stones in temple precincts. Israel appropriated the practice in some periods (Jacob sets up a maṣṣēbāh at Bethel, Gen 28:18; 35:14) but the Canaanite cultic stones were to be destroyed because they were dedicated to Baal or other deities. The tension between this command and the Patriarchal precedents for standing stones reflects Israel's ongoing struggle to distinguish legitimate memorial practice from Canaanite cult.</p>",
        "25": "<p>'Worship the LORD your God, and his blessing will be on your food and water' — the covenant blessing formula connects exclusive worship with material provision: food, water, health, and fertility. In the ancient Near East, material prosperity was understood as divine favor made tangible; the absence of prosperity was interpreted as divine displeasure or divine absence. The Book of the Covenant does not spiritualize the promise — the blessing is physical and concrete. This connection between covenant obedience and material wellbeing runs through Deuteronomy 28 (blessings and curses) and becomes a theological problem in the wisdom literature (Job, Qohelet) when the expected correlation breaks down.</p>",
        "26": "<p>'None will miscarry or be barren in your land' — the covenant's fertility promise addresses the deepest anxiety of agricultural society: the failure of reproduction in human, animal, and plant. Barrenness was understood as divine withholding; fertility was blessing made visible. The promise 'I will give you a full span of life (<em>et-mispar yamekha ʾămalleʾ</em>)' — literally 'I will fill up the number of your days' — guarantees not just long life but life fully lived to its divinely appointed measure. This contrasts with premature death as divine judgment. The fullness-of-days language reappears in Ps 91:16 and in the wisdom literature.</p>",
        "27": "<p>'I will send my terror (<em>ʾêmātî</em>) ahead of you and throw into confusion every nation you encounter' — the divine terror (also <em>ḥittit</em>, panic) is a holy-war concept: YHWH's advance presence paralyzes the enemy with supernatural fear. The Song of the Sea (15:14-16) anticipated this: 'terror and dread fall on them' — and Rahab's words in Josh 2:9-11 confirm it happened. The 'divine panic' motif is attested in other ANE military theology (Hittite annals speak of the storm-god sending panic before the king's army) but in Israel it is used to emphasize that the conquest is YHWH's act, not Israel's military prowess.</p>",
        "28": "<p>'I will send the hornet (<em>ṣirʿāh</em>) ahead of you to drive out the Hivites, Canaanites, and Hittites' — the 'hornet' has been interpreted variously as: (1) literal hornets (insects as divine agent); (2) a metaphor for panic or terror; (3) an identification with the Egyptian scarab/hornet symbol of pharaonic power (suggesting Egyptian military campaigns preceded Israel's entry); or (4) an oblique reference to divine plague. Deuteronomy 7:20 and Joshua 24:12 repeat the promise, and Josh 24:12 explicitly denies it was accomplished by sword and bow — the hornet did the work. The metaphorical reading is most likely: divine terror goes before Israel, not literal insects.</p>",
        "29": "<p>'But I will not drive them out in a single year, because the land would become desolate and the wild animals too numerous for you' — this remarkable verse provides a practical ecological reason for gradual conquest: sudden depopulation of agricultural land creates wilderness that fills with wildlife dangerous to the small Israelite population. The book of Judges reflects this reality — the incomplete conquest left pockets of Canaanite population that became ongoing moral dangers. YHWH's plan for the land is not immediate transformation but gradual, sustainable settlement. The 'little by little' (<em>mĕʿaṭ mĕʿaṭ</em>) principle of v.30 reflects the wisdom of sustainable transition.</p>",
        "30": "<p>'Little by little I will drive them out before you, until you have grown enough to take possession of the land' — the conquest is calibrated to Israel's growth capacity. This verse qualifies the total-conquest commands elsewhere: the promised annihilation of the Canaanites is a theological ideal (removing all idolatry from the land) that is tempered by practical wisdom about what Israel can actually hold. The book of Judges begins with the tribes' failures to complete the conquest (Judges 1), and traces the spiritual consequences of incomplete obedience — the Canaanite remnants do exactly what v.33 warns: they become a snare.</p>",
        "31": "<p>'I will establish your borders from the Red Sea to the Mediterranean Sea, and from the desert to the Euphrates River' — this is the maximal extent of the promised land, corresponding roughly to the territory of the Davidic-Solomonic empire at its greatest extent (1 Kgs 4:21-24). The four compass points define a vast territory that Israel never fully occupied in any period. The promise functions as a theological horizon: the complete covenant fulfillment lies ahead, even when the present reality is partial. Revelation's vision of the new earth draws on this expansive territorial promise as a type of the ultimate restoration.</p>",
        "32": "<p>'Do not make any covenant (<em>bĕrît</em>) with them or with their gods' — the covenant exclusivity principle applied politically: Israel is not to enter treaty relationships with the Canaanite nations because treaties involved reciprocal worship obligations. In the ANE, inter-state treaties were sealed with oaths invoking both parties' deities; ratifying a treaty with the Canaanites would necessarily involve acknowledging the validity of their gods. The kings who violated this command by making alliances with surrounding nations (Solomon's foreign wives, Ahab's marriage to Jezebel) brought precisely the religious syncretism this law anticipated.</p>",
        "33": "<p>'Do not let them live in your land, or they will cause you to sin against me' — the prophylactic logic: the Canaanite populations in the land will inevitably introduce their religious practices to Israel, and Israel will inevitably be attracted to them. Judges confirms this prediction point-by-point: wherever the Canaanites were not expelled, Israel adopted their worship (Judg 2:12-13; 3:5-7). The NT applies the underlying principle to spiritual warfare: 'Do not be misled: evil company corrupts good character' (1 Cor 15:33); 'Do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers' (2 Cor 6:14) — both draw on the same protective-separation logic.</p>"
    },
    "24": {
        "1": "<p>The covenant ratification ceremony (ch.24) is one of the most significant events in the OT: the formal establishment of the Sinai covenant between YHWH and Israel. The four-tier structure of who may approach — Moses alone at the summit, Aaron and Nadab and Abihu at a middle level, the seventy elders lower, and the people at the base — reflects the graduated holiness structure of sacred space that will be built into the tabernacle's design (most holy place → holy place → outer court → camp). The seventy elders (representing the full body of Israel; cf. the 70 nations in Gen 10) are included in the vision but at a subordinate level.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'Moses alone is to approach the LORD; the others must not come near' — the exclusive mediation of Moses at the summit structures the covenant: YHWH speaks to Israel through a single authorized mediator. This sets the pattern for all subsequent Israelite prophecy (YHWH speaks through a prophet, not directly to the community) and anticipates the NT's category of Jesus as the unique mediator (1 Tim 2:5: 'there is one mediator between God and mankind, the man Christ Jesus'). The graduated approach — elders nearer than people, Moses nearer than elders — reflects the incarnational logic: those who bear more responsibility come closer.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'The people responded with one voice: “Everything the LORD has said we will do”' — the unanimous covenant acceptance is the formal response that constitutes Israel as a covenant community. In ANE suzerain-vassal treaties, the vassal's formal acceptance of the treaty terms created the binding covenant relationship. The phrase 'all the words which the LORD has spoken' (<em>kol-hadĕbārîm ʾăšer dibber YHWH</em>) refers to the Decalogue and the Book of the Covenant (Exod 20-23). Israel's triple consent — here, after the blood-sprinkling (v.7), and again (v.8) — shows the ceremony is structured to make the commitment irrevocable and communally witnessed.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'Moses then wrote down everything the LORD had said' — this is the first explicit reference to Moses as a writer in the Pentateuch, and the written document ('the Book of the Covenant') is immediately incorporated into the ratification ceremony. The writing creates a permanent, authoritative record that can be read publicly (v.7). ANE suzerain-vassal treaties always included a written document deposited in the sanctuary of the deities and read publicly at regular intervals (Deut 31:10-11 commands a seven-year public reading of the Torah). The twelve pillars Moses erects represent the twelve tribes as witnesses to the covenant — a standard ANE treaty feature.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Young men (<em>naʿărê bĕnê yiśrāʾēl</em>) offer the burnt offerings and peace offerings — before the Levitical priesthood is established (Exod 28-29; Lev 8-9), sacrifices are offered by designated laymen from the community. This confirms that the Levitical priesthood is not a creation-order institution but a covenant-specific institution established at Sinai. The peace offerings (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>) — whose blood will be used in the covenant ratification — are distinct from the burnt offerings: they involve a shared meal between the offerer, the priest, and YHWH (symbolically), making them the natural sacrifice for covenant-sealing.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Moses divides the blood into two halves: half against the altar (YHWH's side of the covenant) and half reserved for the people (v.8). This binary division is unique in OT ritual and mirrors the covenant structure: YHWH and Israel are the two parties, and the blood bonds both. The altar represents YHWH; the people represent Israel. The blood that bridges them is the covenant's sealing medium — the life of the sacrifice stands in for the lives of the parties who are bound by death-oath. If either party breaks the covenant, they call down on themselves what happened to the sacrifice.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'He took the Book of the Covenant and read it to the people. They responded, “We will do everything the LORD has said; we will obey”' (<em>naʿăśeh wĕnišmāʿ</em>) — the Hebrew word order is significant: 'we will do and we will hear/obey.' The Talmud (Shabbat 88a) treats this as Israel's greatest moment: they committed to do before they had fully heard all the implications, a contrast to normal human contract negotiation. The public reading of the covenant document before the people's formal acceptance mirrors ANE treaty practice: the vassal must be informed before consenting. The people's response makes them personally responsible for what was read.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'This is the blood of the covenant that the LORD has made with you' — Moses's words at the blood-sprinkling are the most directly quoted OT text in the NT's eucharistic tradition. Jesus at the Last Supper says: 'This is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many' (Matt 26:28; Mark 14:24) — an unmistakable echo of Moses's words in Exod 24:8. Hebrews 9:18-20 cites the Sinai blood-sprinkling as the prototype of covenant inauguration and argues that the new covenant's ratification through Christ's blood is the same pattern carried to its ultimate fulfillment. The covenant is not complete until blood seals it.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The seventy elders (plus Moses, Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu — seventy-four people) ascend the mountain for the theophanic meal. The number seventy recurs throughout the OT as the representative total of Israel: the seventy descendants who went down to Egypt (Gen 46:27), the seventy nations of Gen 10, the seventy elders appointed by Moses (Num 11:16-25), and Jesus's sending of seventy disciples (Luke 10:1). The seventy elders represent the entire covenant community; their vision of God on the mountain is Israel's representative encounter with the divine presence.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'They saw the God of Israel. Under his feet was something like a pavement made of lapis lazuli, as bright as the sky itself' — this is one of the most audacious theophanies in Scripture. The elders see YHWH (though the focus falls on 'under his feet' rather than his full form, consistent with the tradition that the full divine face cannot be seen by mortals, Exod 33:20). Lapis lazuli (<em>sappîr</em>) — the vivid blue semi-precious stone mined in Afghanistan and traded throughout the ancient Near East — was associated with the sky and with royal/divine magnificence. Ezekiel's vision of the divine throne (Ezek 1:26; 10:1) also features a sapphire pavement, directly recalling this text.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'But God did not raise his hand against these leaders of the Israelites; they saw God, and they ate and drank' — the eating and drinking in YHWH's presence on the mountain is the covenant meal, sealing the treaty relationship. In ANE treaty practice, the covenant meal shared between the suzerain and vassal ratified the relationship — it was not merely celebratory but constitutive. The fact that YHWH 'did not raise his hand' is the narrator's way of emphasizing the extraordinary grace of this encounter: the humans expected to die from divine exposure (Exod 33:20; Judg 13:22) but instead ate in YHWH's presence. This is the prototype of the eschatological banquet (Isa 25:6-8; Rev 19:9).</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Come up to me on the mountain and stay here, and I will give you the tablets of stone with the law and commandments I have written for their instruction' — Moses is summoned to receive the stone tablets of the Decalogue (later given in ch.31:18). The tablets are described as written by YHWH himself (Exod 31:18: 'written by the finger of God'), uniquely distinguishing the Decalogue from the Book of the Covenant (which Moses wrote, v.4). The divine inscribing of the Decalogue signals its foundational status within the covenant — it is not merely the report of a human mediator but the direct expression of YHWH's own authority.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Joshua is introduced here as Moses's aide (<em>mĕšārēt</em>, servant/minister) — the term used for Elisha's service to Elijah and for priestly service at the sanctuary. Joshua's presence with Moses partway up the mountain (he apparently waits while Moses continues alone) is the first indication of his role as Moses's successor. The name Yĕhôšûaʿ (Joshua) means 'YHWH saves' — the same root as Yēšûaʿ (Jesus). The coincidence is noted in Heb 4:8: Joshua could not give the people their ultimate rest; only Jesus can.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'Aaron and Hur are with you. Anyone involved in a dispute can go to them' — Aaron and Hur function as the governing council in Moses's forty-day absence. The two men represent civil (Hur, the military leader of Exod 17:10) and religious (Aaron, the high priest designate) authority. Their joint leadership during Moses's absence is a pattern for shared governance. The failure they experience — Aaron's capitulation to the golden calf demand (ch.32) — will be the defining failure of the transitional period, showing that the people require the ongoing presence of the singular mediator Moses rather than divided leadership.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The cloud (<em>ʿānān</em>) that covers Sinai when Moses ascends is the same pillar of cloud that has guided Israel through the wilderness — the cloud is the visible manifestation of the glory (<em>kābôd</em>) of YHWH. The cloud-cover serves as a veil: the divine glory is present but not immediately visible to the people below. Six days of waiting precede Moses's summons on the seventh day — a pattern mirroring creation (six days + seventh day of divine rest) and anticipating the tabernacle construction where the cloud-glory will descend on the completed sanctuary (Exod 40:34-35).</p>",
        "16": "<p>'The glory of the LORD settled (<em>wayyiškōn</em>) on Mount Sinai' — the verb <em>šākan</em> (to dwell, to tabernacle) is the root of the noun <em>miškan</em> (tabernacle, dwelling) and the later Jewish theological concept of the <em>šĕkînāh</em> (divine presence). YHWH's glory 'tabernacling' on Sinai anticipates the tabernacle that will be built to house that same glory. John 1:14 uses the same word: 'the Word became flesh and tabernacled (<em>ἐσκήνωσεν</em>) among us, and we have seen his glory.' The Sinai theophany is thus the proto-tabernacle: the glory that will permanently dwell in the sanctuary first rests on the mountain.</p>",
        "17": "<p>'To the Israelites the glory of the LORD looked like a consuming fire on top of the mountain' — the fire theophany (also Exod 3:2; 19:18) is the standard Sinai image in later OT memory: Deuteronomy consistently describes Sinai as 'the mountain burning with fire' (Deut 4:11; 5:23; 9:15). Hebrews 12:18-24 uses this description as the foil for the new covenant's 'Mount Zion' — the terrifying mountain that cannot be touched (Sinai) contrasted with the joyful assembly of the firstborn (Zion). The consuming fire of divine glory is the same fire that will later consume the tabernacle sacrifices (Lev 9:24) and the NT's tongues of fire at Pentecost (Acts 2:3).</p>",
        "18": "<p>'Moses entered the cloud as he went on up the mountain. And he stayed on the mountain forty days and forty nights' — the forty-day period on Sinai is the paradigmatic period of intimate divine encounter. Moses's two forty-day sojourns on Sinai (this one and Exod 34:28) frame the golden calf apostasy between them. Elijah's forty-day journey to Horeb (1 Kgs 19:8) and Jesus's forty days of testing in the wilderness (Matt 4:2) both deliberately echo the Moses-Sinai pattern. In OT typology, forty days or forty years marks a complete period of formation/testing before a new phase of redemptive history begins.</p>"
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', existing)
    for ch in ['22', '23', '24']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with context commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
